WEBVTT

00:10.747 --> 00:21.466
Okay, this is Ron Shorn at University of 
California, Berkeley,

00:10.747 --> 00:21.466
interviewing Peter Boyce. And let's start at the 
beginning. Peter, what's your full name? It's

00:25.733 --> 00:27.215
Peter Bradford Boyce. And when and where were you 
born? Born in New York City on November 30th, 1936.

00:31.904 --> 00:36.231
How did you first get interested in astronomy? I 
took a course from Bart Bach at Harvard. What were

00:39.628 --> 00:41.109
you majoring in then? I was going to be pre-med. And 
one course in astronomy, and it was all over.

00:47.036 --> 00:57.707
Actually, I was prepared for it because my father, 
we lived in the country, moved out of New York City

00:47.036 --> 00:57.707
at the age of one and a half, one of the best 
decisions in my life, I think. And moved to the

00:57.728 --> 01:02.893
country, and my father was very interested in the 
seasons. We did farming and the change of the sun

01:02.953 --> 01:06.437
and the return of the sun. that allowed us to start 
planning again was really important to my father,

01:06.805 --> 01:14.237
who was a novelist by trade. And so we used to go out 
and look at the northern lights and the

01:15.159 --> 01:21.810
constellations appearance of a dog star showed 
that winter was coming along. And so we always were

01:26.318 --> 01:28.700
interested in the sky. And when I was in high 
school, I went to the school whose football coach

01:29.480 --> 01:36.727
was the father of Walter Orr Roberts. And Walter 
Roberts came in and gave a couple of lectures in the

01:37.587 --> 01:41.971
school. And of course, the kind of thing he was 
doing at the high altitude observatory and making

01:42.952 --> 01:52.000
time lapse movies of the solar prominence is 
really exciting to a young kid. And I got

01:56.693 --> 02:02.500
interested enough to want to build my own 
telescope, which I did in high school. But I wasn't

02:02.940 --> 02:05.604
thinking of that as a career. I'm not even sure I 
knew that astronomy was a viable career at that

02:05.684 --> 02:09.769
time. And I went to Harvard, really set to major in 
pre-med because I wanted to be a doctor. had a

02:20.330 --> 02:31.462
semester course to spare in chemistry, because I 
took the full year of chemistry in half a year as an

02:20.330 --> 02:31.462
advanced course. And I had a year of science to 
spare and took an astronomy course, and that was

02:31.482 --> 02:35.967
it. Did you switch majors? Well, I don't think we 
had to really declare a major in the freshman year,

02:39.651 --> 02:48.480
but I'm sure after that, I immediately declared as 
a sophomore be an astronomy major, and we had 11

02:49.085 --> 03:04.282
other astronomy undergraduate majors that year, 
and they set up a whole series of courses designed

02:49.085 --> 03:04.282
to accommodate both the astronomy major students 
and the beginning graduate students. So we had a

03:05.123 --> 03:13.673
mixture of courses that were absolutely 
fantastic as a preparation for further work in

03:05.123 --> 03:13.673
astronomy. What year did you get your bachelor's 
degree? 1958. Then where did you go to graduate

03:18.565 --> 03:20.607
school? I went to grad school in Michigan. Married 
a woman who was a year behind me, and she

03:23.310 --> 03:29.578
accelerated, and I waited six months. So I got to 
Michigan in January of 59. And when I came to

03:34.363 --> 03:40.810
Michigan, it was a time of great change. And they 
came to Michigan to study under the faculty of

03:40.891 --> 03:48.319
Aller, Liller, Miller, Mueller, Moeller, and 
Goldberg. And by the time I left, all of them had

03:48.518 --> 03:53.947
departed the scene except Freeman Miller. Yeah, 
that was described as a supernova explosion.

03:57.333 --> 03:58.535
Yeah, something like that. The legislature 
wouldn't give them a big telescope. That's right,

04:00.919 --> 04:01.881
yeah. So I got my doctorate in 63. Okay, who was your 
thesis advisor and what did you do? I worked on the

04:10.034 --> 04:29.634
Orion Nebula, used Bob Tull's scanner that he 
built for his thesis, photoelectric spectrum

04:10.034 --> 04:29.634
scanner, single channel, and observed the 
hydrogen bomber decrement in the Orion Nebula.

04:30.495 --> 04:37.982
And by comparing the strengths of the lines with 
the theoretical calculations, I was able to show

04:30.495 --> 04:37.982
that There was a lot of dust in the nebula or in front 
of the nebula. It was central with the nebula,

04:42.258 --> 04:44.364
however. I forgot to mention the date. This is June 
7, 1993.

04:52.863 --> 04:56.707
Okay, you got your PhD, and then presumably you got 
a job. I got a job at Lowell Observatory. How did you

04:59.249 --> 05:01.131
get that kind of job? Well, John Hall had done some 
polarization studies in the Orion Nebula, and I

05:01.831 --> 05:19.528
found an AAS abstract of it and no other reference 
to it, so I called him and wrote him and asked for

05:01.831 --> 05:19.528
further data, and he sent me some data and said it 
was never published, though. But it, again, was

05:20.032 --> 05:26.081
sort of confirmatory that there was a lot of dust 
involved in the nebular complex. So I

05:28.225 --> 05:43.408
said I was getting out soon, and also just because 
of that, I asked him if there were any jobs around

05:28.225 --> 05:43.408
Lowell and got a letter back inviting me to come and 
interview. So Bill Sinton had gotten... NSF

05:46.998 --> 05:50.463
grant, I guess, and had money to hire somebody. 
When did you arrive at Moab? 1963 in September.

05:57.753 --> 06:03.922
That September, about a week after I arrived, we 
had an observing run with the interferometer. I

06:04.022 --> 06:05.925
knew nothing about interferometry. It was an 
interferometric spectrometer. a root keel prism

06:10.454 --> 06:18.423
interferometer in the 2 micron range. And we had 10 
clear days, 10 clear nights, actually. And what

06:25.171 --> 06:25.932
telescope? Well, at that time, it was the 69-inch 
telescope at Anderson Mesa at Lowell. And it was

06:34.602 --> 06:40.208
the original Ohio State, Ohio Wesleyan 
telescope. And so we worked our butts off. And I

06:43.046 --> 06:53.957
thought, boy, this is quite different from my 
thesis in Michigan, where I actually went to a New

06:43.046 --> 06:53.957
Year's Eve party one clear night instead of going 
out to the telescope. And it was March before I

06:54.318 --> 06:58.061
could get back on the telescope again because of 
the weather. So I thought I was in heaven. Of

06:59.683 --> 07:02.927
course, that's the same thing as the Brouwer 
fortnight. I never got 10 clear nights in a row

07:02.967 --> 07:07.191
again on my whole 10 years at Lowell. It was an 
exciting time. What objects were you observing?

07:10.946 --> 07:14.010
We were observing cool stars, long period 
variable stars. And one of the, the only place we

07:14.691 --> 07:30.394
published it was in Stein Telescope, but we did 
detect water, the water bands in Tri-Signe and

07:14.691 --> 07:30.394
showed that they went away at maximum light and 
were strongly there at minimum light. Global, of

07:30.374 --> 07:39.630
course, is most famous for planetary work, but 
they always did, from the very beginning, do

07:30.374 --> 07:39.630
stellar and galactic work. Well, that's right. 
Bill was doing a lot of planetary work originally,

07:41.733 --> 07:54.354
and I think he kind of got discouraged, I guess, 
when he had this false positive detection of the

07:41.733 --> 07:54.354
C-H band on Mars. And so he was... doing stellar 
astronomy at that time. But he liked to do the

08:00.565 --> 08:01.948
instruments. He liked to fiddle with them and make 
them work. And building on Larry Mertz's

08:05.033 --> 08:18.117
interferometry experience where Larry and Bill 
Sinton crossed paths at Harvard while I was an

08:05.033 --> 08:18.117
undergraduate there, actually, And Bill had 
built this interferometer, and it was really

08:18.097 --> 08:25.987
working very well. I mean, we got some nice spectra 
for the time. Of course, these days, what we would

08:29.552 --> 08:35.419
spend all night on, they can do in 10 minutes. When 
you started at Lowell, who was on the staff there?

08:38.984 --> 08:39.304
Do you remember? Well, John Hall was the director. 
E.C. Slipher was still alive, buried in the midst

08:43.111 --> 08:56.694
of his cigar box filing system of all the plates of 
Mars that they had ever taken at various

08:43.111 --> 08:56.694
Lowell-funded telescopes. Bill Sinton was 
there. Bill Tift was there. I

09:02.765 --> 09:10.518
was trying to remember who was there when we first 
came. Some of the exciting people. I think

09:12.501 --> 09:22.377
when I showed up that year, Karl Rakos from Austria 
was there for the first time.

09:23.757 --> 09:27.023
Wojtek Cieminski had been there and gone. I

09:27.043 --> 09:35.279
don't remember who else right now was on the staff 
at the beginning. When you got there, was there

09:35.921 --> 09:38.506
much planetary work being done? There wasn't a lot 
of planetary work at that time. The Slifers were

09:45.138 --> 09:58.570
taking some pictures, but there was a lot of 
preparation, I think, for the coming Planetary

09:45.138 --> 09:58.570
Center and excitement. I guess the big thing that 
was going on was the ACIC project, the Lunar

09:59.491 --> 10:07.798
Mapping Project, and the Aeronautical Chart and 
Information Center. There were as many people

10:08.379 --> 10:13.423
doing that as we had people on the Lowell staff. And 
they tied up the 24-inch telescope most of the

10:14.095 --> 10:25.067
time, doing a lot of visual filling in of details on 
the map.

10:28.430 --> 10:37.580
When you went there, did you feel that real 
astronomers looked down on people that worked at

10:28.430 --> 10:37.580
Lowell Territory? Well, I was too naive to know 
whether to consider that. I was just charged up to

10:43.703 --> 10:47.748
be going to a place that had such a name. I

10:47.788 --> 10:54.976
was fairly well treated, I must say. And every 
paper that I was given, I'd given at meetings and so

10:54.996 --> 11:01.283
forth. It was received pretty well. I didn't seem 
to feel too discriminated against. What I did feel

11:07.490 --> 11:10.613
very strongly was that the old-time planetary 
astronomers would look down upon, people who

11:11.234 --> 11:19.983
would look at either an image. I mean, E.C. Slipher 
would pick an image out. Now, he obviously was

11:23.647 --> 11:39.064
looking through the telescope at the same time, 
and this colored his vision of what he saw on the

11:23.647 --> 11:39.064
photograph, but he would point out things and say, 
this is low-lying morning haze, and this over here

11:23.647 --> 11:39.064
is afternoon cumulus. when he had no basis for 
being able to differentiate that kind of thing at

11:39.247 --> 11:47.360
all on Mars. And so I also was very skeptical that 
this was real science, just having somebody sit

11:47.921 --> 11:58.859
there and give their opinions of what they were 
actually seeing. What was the attitude of the

11:59.780 --> 12:05.389
staff members towards the late Percival Lowell?

12:07.850 --> 12:14.097
Oh, I guess we're pretty grateful that he had 
founded the observatory. We're grateful that he

12:14.157 --> 12:16.220
sent A.E. Douglas out looking for a place and 
grateful of the citizens of Flagstaff who met the

12:16.260 --> 12:34.060
train with a brass band and escorted him up Mars 
Hill or what was to become Mars Hill and grateful

12:16.260 --> 12:34.060
that it was clear and rather good observing 
conditions at the time he was searching for the

12:16.260 --> 12:34.060
site. You know, Lowell had a, I guess we sort of 
wished that he had not passed away so soon because

12:35.440 --> 13:00.773
clearly the observatory was eking along hand to 
mouth on the endowment, the rather minuscule

12:35.440 --> 13:00.773
endowment which the observatory had, and we all 
felt, I think, that it would have been much bigger

13:01.023 --> 13:12.919
had Lowell survived a little bit longer and the 
estate hadn't been in such a turmoil and put such a

13:01.023 --> 13:12.919
pinch on the observatory during the 30s and 40s. 
When you were there, was Lowell still in the string

13:13.680 --> 13:22.912
and bailing wire hand-to-mouth existence that it 
was famous for? Oh yeah, sure. I mean, that was very

13:25.340 --> 13:50.250
frustrating at times, and you couldn't buy enough 
screwdrivers to be sure that you always had one at

13:25.340 --> 13:50.250
the telescope, although Henry Giklis used to say 
he was absolutely certain that the top of Anderson

13:25.340 --> 13:50.250
Mesa was littered with screwdrivers six inches 
deep somewhere, because he had bought so many. You

13:50.956 --> 13:53.100
stayed at Lowell for 10 years. Yes. And what did you 
work on? Well, I started out to work with Bill

13:55.204 --> 14:01.235
Sinton and then on the Orion Nebula again. And then 
I built a spectrum scanner funded by the

14:01.275 --> 14:14.500
observatory itself and started to use that on 
planetary nebulae.

14:16.555 --> 14:44.622
Then I built, following Carl Rakosh's visit, 
where he developed what he called an area scanner,

14:16.555 --> 14:44.622
which was a way to wipe a slit across the star, a 
double star in particular, and get a profile of the

14:16.555 --> 14:44.622
two components, which you could then deconvolve 
and get much more accurate photoelectric

14:16.555 --> 14:44.622
magnitudes for stars which were normally too 
close to resolve in conventional photometry.

14:45.732 --> 15:12.398
this was such a powerful technique that i began to 
use it and put a spectrum i mean a scanning aperture

14:45.732 --> 15:12.398
in front of my spectrum scanner at scanning and 
right angles to the dispersion and i used then the

14:45.732 --> 15:12.398
spectrum scanner as a movable square bandpass 
very well defined bandpass filter and

15:13.070 --> 15:29.532
turn to my love of gaseous nebulae and would scan 
these planetary nebulae and H-alpha, H-beta, and

15:13.070 --> 15:29.532
the oxygen lines and so forth, and look at the 
structure of the planetary nebulae. And then one

15:30.253 --> 15:35.881
night, Mars was up in the sky, and people were kind 
of excited because it was an opposition. And I

15:36.041 --> 15:36.942
looked at it. And of course, it's a gorgeous sight 
for somebody who'd never paid much attention to

15:37.002 --> 15:42.570
planets before. And I said, well, I'll try to scan 
it. Scanning a planetary nebula meant for me, a

15:48.950 --> 16:09.418
planetary nebula meant for me being on there for 
half an hour, 45 minutes, and then building up

15:48.950 --> 16:09.418
enough statistics that you would have a 
reasonably noise-free profile of the

15:48.950 --> 16:09.418
distribution of the element you were looking at 
across the nebula. So I did the same thing to Mars,

16:11.719 --> 16:19.012
and in 30 seconds, I had the biggest, brightest, 
most noise-free profile that I'd ever seen in my

16:11.719 --> 16:19.012
life. And so I thought, well, this is maybe 
something I should do. And I looked at Mars. I

16:26.745 --> 16:27.607
looked in the red. I looked in the blue. And the 
profiles were so different. And of course, you

16:32.353 --> 16:36.761
can't see any details on the surface in blue. And 
you could in red. And I thought, well, gee, I could

16:39.044 --> 16:41.889
measure some of the differences here. And I began 
to look at the planetary literature to see what was

16:41.949 --> 16:52.367
known and what kind of accurate measurements had 
been made of the surface photometry of the

16:41.949 --> 16:52.367
different areas of the planet. I found there was 
nothing, really nothing. And I said, well, this is

16:55.518 --> 16:57.000
fine. So I started to work on the planets then. Did 
you ever get any NASA support for that work, or was

17:01.245 --> 17:05.010
it observatory? If I got, well, John Hall had the 
peculiar, and as I later found out, absolutely

17:06.492 --> 17:24.394
false assumption that if you put in a proposal and 
it was turned down, you got a black mark in the

17:06.492 --> 17:24.394
agency's book. And so you should never put in a 
proposal unless you were absolutely sure it was

17:25.387 --> 17:30.536
going to be funded. And he didn't think that my 
suggestions for proposals would immediately get

17:31.277 --> 17:38.329
funded, and so he didn't want me to send them in. I 
think that my salary was partly paid by the NASA

17:39.091 --> 17:44.059
contract from time to time. This was after the 
Planetary Center had been established and Bill

17:44.099 --> 17:49.048
Baum had come. Ten years after you came, had the 
observatory, had NASA money really changed? Oh

17:57.883 --> 17:59.445
yes, it changed it a lot. First of all, the 
Planetary Center gave us a new building, really

18:01.327 --> 18:16.403
major facilities

18:01.327 --> 18:16.403
for a lot of things and money for instrumentation 
that was highly welcome. and made a major impact.

18:20.521 --> 18:30.779
We expanded the staff in the workshops and things 
like that, but it just made a difference in night

18:20.521 --> 18:30.779
and day. At the same time, Bill Sinton and I had 
gotten into using locally available computers

18:36.717 --> 18:48.211
first down at the business school at the NAU, which 
was the first computer in Flagstaff, an old IBM

18:36.717 --> 18:48.211
1620. And we rewrote the Fourier transform 
program that Bill was using to produce the spectra

18:48.231 --> 19:03.489
from his interferograms to run on the 1620. And 
then we... finally persuaded Lowell that they had

19:06.383 --> 19:24.329
to buy an IBM 1130, which was sort of the first 
reasonably priced computer that a smaller

19:06.383 --> 19:24.329
institution could afford to really get that had 
sufficient capability to be a worthwhile

19:06.383 --> 19:24.329
computer. So we got the 1130, and Bill and I were put 
in charge of it, and I eventually became sort of the

19:24.389 --> 19:32.340
director the de facto director of the computer 
center for four years. After Lowell, where did you

19:36.117 --> 19:40.022
go? After Lowell, I came to NSF as a program 
director for astronomical instrumentation for

19:41.304 --> 19:54.083
supposedly for two years and stayed for six, I 
guess, 73 to 79. And then where did you go?

19:59.641 --> 20:27.336
last year or the next to the last year that stay at 
nsf i got a department of commerce science and

19:59.641 --> 20:27.336
technology fellowship and spent a year on capitol 
hill working for mo udall came back discovered

19:59.641 --> 20:27.336
that the nsf as an agency didn't want to know about 
my experience on the hill didn't want to put it to

19:59.641 --> 20:27.336
any use at all and in fact the congressional office 
at nsf thought that any suggestions I made were

20:27.907 --> 20:57.475
poaching on their territory and so I was really 
what I had learned was just never put to use at all

20:27.907 --> 20:57.475
and I was so disgusted that this kind of thing was 
going on when I could see that there were things

20:27.907 --> 20:57.475
that NSF should do to change its image in Congress 
and I applied for the job of

20:58.028 --> 21:16.967
executive officer of the AAS, which at that point 
came open, I sort of applied as a lark and

20:58.028 --> 21:16.967
discovered that my ideas of where the society 
should go and the search committee's ideas were

20:58.028 --> 21:16.967
really so congruent as to be a remarkable match. 
And they hired me, and that's where I've been ever

21:17.607 --> 21:20.290
since. Well, as the executive director, you have 
the continuity that the other officers lack. One

21:28.454 --> 21:47.552
thing I want to ask you from your standpoint

21:28.454 --> 21:47.552
is the creation of separate sub-societies, such 
as the original one, which is high energy

21:28.454 --> 21:47.552
astrophysics, but then vision for planetary 
astronomy. There was a lot of worry that this would

21:47.572 --> 21:51.936
split up astronomy and all that sort of stuff. Do 
you think that the, well, what do you think about

21:51.956 --> 21:57.921
these divisions? I have mixed emotions.

22:02.407 --> 22:04.709
I think by and large it's a very important thing. 
When the planetary division, let me start with the

22:05.109 --> 22:17.660
high energy astrophysics division, they

22:05.109 --> 22:17.660
have to be members of the parent society in order to 
be members of the division. And that has worked out

22:18.401 --> 22:20.863
very well. It's given an impetus to the high energy 
astrophysics, which I think was very important at

22:28.259 --> 22:30.882
the time the division was started. Well, weren't 
those guys threatening to go to the American

22:31.343 --> 22:34.788
Geophysical Union? No, this is the high energy. 
Oh, this is high energy. Then I think the first

22:38.953 --> 22:44.621
division, in fact, was the planetary division. 
And I think that also was very important because

22:45.121 --> 22:52.131
planetary astronomy sort of had three homes. 
There were a number of people who were astronomers

22:52.171 --> 22:55.515
and belonged to the AAS. There were a number of 
people who were atmospheric physicists who

22:55.765 --> 23:04.512
belonged to the, well, I suppose the American 
Meteorological Society. And then the planetary

23:05.593 --> 23:10.538
surface geologists mostly belonged to AGU. And 
there was no one place where they could feel at

23:11.218 --> 23:14.461
home. And part of the major rationale for 
establishing the planetary division was, in

23:14.521 --> 23:25.030
fact, to give them a home where they didn't have to 
pay too much in the way of dues, so we did have the

23:25.398 --> 23:49.443
affiliate membership, division affiliate 
membership, with very low dues, but it provided an

23:25.398 --> 23:49.443
opportunity where they all had a home and you could 
meet and have all these people attend the meeting

23:25.398 --> 23:49.443
without having to pay the much higher dues of the 
parent society. And I think that's a very

23:49.463 --> 23:54.628
important function, and I think it's been very, 
very healthy for the planetary field as a whole.

23:58.624 --> 24:03.228
People always make comments like, well, it's too 
bad that they're diverging and everything. But I

24:03.288 --> 24:08.814
just wonder in the good old days, for example, did 
Alistair pay any attention whatsoever to

24:03.288 --> 24:08.814
planetary studies? Oh, no. There was no. That was 
getting back to one of our earlier questions. That

24:14.960 --> 24:20.886
was a really important thing to highlight the fact 
that, in fact, people were doing what I was doing

24:21.878 --> 24:36.058
and trying to bring some kind of modern technology 
and accuracy and real scientific judgment to the

24:21.878 --> 24:36.058
planetary studies. And that was just not very well 
appreciated at all by the conventional stellar

24:36.819 --> 24:42.587
astronomers. I mean, we weren't alone. The solar 
physicists feel, have felt left out from time to

24:46.545 --> 24:52.053
time as well. And I think having the division and 
having the ability to present talks at the main AAS

24:53.836 --> 25:10.482
meetings was very, very important in helping the 
rest of the community to become at least more aware

24:53.836 --> 25:10.482
that Planetary science was not just somebody 
holding up a photograph and saying, well, that's

25:11.103 --> 25:18.392
ground haze over there on the limb. And

25:19.534 --> 25:30.968
now they understand that if you're going to study 
the circulation of the Martian atmosphere, you

25:19.534 --> 25:30.968
have to really do... pretty complex models, even 
though there's no oceans. It makes it a simpler

25:35.650 --> 25:37.493
system, the model. But you model that, and then you 
compare with the observations, and you have the

25:37.773 --> 25:43.921
spacecraft going there. But it's all done by, it 
isn't just pictures anymore, but it's real good

25:43.981 --> 25:51.009
science that's being done. And I think that's 
appreciated much more now than it was. And I think

25:54.874 --> 25:57.057
the formation of the division by giving them a 
strong point to stand on and help the assimilation

25:57.762 --> 26:17.305
or the understanding of planetary astronomy and 
the assimilation of planetary astronomy into

25:57.762 --> 26:17.305
the general overall astronomy picture. Well, 
you've just about answered my next question, is do

26:17.585 --> 26:26.335
you think that planetary astronomer has a higher 
standing now among real quote unquote

26:17.585 --> 26:26.335
astronomers than it did when you got your PhD? Oh, 
yeah, absolutely. No question about it. And it's

26:31.251 --> 26:37.759
partly due to the influx of NASA money and the jobs. 
But that isn't all. I mean, at the beginning, I

26:41.803 --> 26:50.533
think that the sort of consensus would be that the 
and you want to treat this kind of carefully, I

26:51.543 --> 27:04.301
think, but I think the consensus was the original 
people funded by NASA were thought among the

26:51.543 --> 27:04.301
community to be those who couldn't get jobs in real 
astrophysics. But as we get more and more people

27:05.142 --> 27:20.925
coming in from atmospheric physics and 
geophysics,

27:05.142 --> 27:20.925
